 I developed Monte-Carlo simulations for trading strategy backtesting.
 By design,
 algorithmic trading processes communicated with the interface process via named pipes and were woken by the latter when a price update was received.
 So I programmed a Python script that mimicked the price updates sent over the pipes but replaced them with historical prices or simulated prices.
 The historical prices were real-time prices that had been received by the interface program and stored in a database,
 whereas the simulated prices were generated by Monte-Carlo simulations,
 using models such as the Geometric Brownian Motion and the Heston model.
\end_layout

